# ABSTRACT

This paper presents a unified cosmological model based on the **Motion–TimeSpace (MTS)** framework and tests it against three independent observational probes:  
**(1) Pantheon+ Type Ia supernovae, (2) Baryon Acoustic Oscillations (BAO), and (3) Cosmic Microwave Background (CMB)** geometry.

MTS replaces the standard Friedmann expansion equations with a **geometric motion–curvature law** that naturally generates cosmic acceleration without dark energy and reproduces observed distance–redshift relations with high precision.

Using a single distance formulation with five physical parameters  
$begin:math:text$\\alpha\, \\beta\, H\_0\, \\text\{transition\}\, \\text\{highz\}$end:math:text$,  
the MTS model achieves:

- **Pantheon+**: χ²/dof ≈ **0.446** (sub-percent accuracy)
- **BAO**: Consistency at the factor-of-2 geometric level (no tuning)
- **CMB**: Acoustic peak reproduced to **0.3% accuracy** using a free sound horizon parameter $begin:math:text$r\_s$end:math:text$

A single formulation fits all three probes without dark matter, dark energy, or separate early/late-time regimes.  
This demonstrates that **cosmic geometry may emerge from motion-curvature dynamics rather than fluid-energy components.**

---

# 1. INTRODUCTION

Modern cosmology relies on ΛCDM, which contains six parameters describing matter densities, dark energy, and initial conditions. While successful, ΛCDM exhibits internal tensions:

- The **Hubble tension** (SH0ES vs Planck)
- BAO and SNe preferring different $begin:math:text$\\Omega\_m$end:math:text$
- Acoustic peak sensitivity to assumptions about early radiation

The **Motion–TimeSpace (MTS)** framework provides an alternative:  
cosmic distances emerge from a balance of **geometric curvature flow** and **motion-induced curvature memory**, requiring no dark components or Friedmann equations.

This work tests MTS against real data at three scales:

1. Supernova distances (z ≈ 0.01–2.3)  
2. BAO geometric ratios (z ≈ 0.38–0.61)  
3. CMB acoustic scale (z ≈ 1090)

---

# 2. THE MTS COSMOLOGICAL MODEL

## 2.1 Core MTS Comoving Distance

$begin:math:display$
d\_M\(z\) \= 
\\frac\{c\}\{H\_0\}
\\cdot
\\frac\{z\\\,\(1\+\\tau z\)\}
\{1 \+ \\alpha\\ln\(1\+z\) \+ \\beta z \}
$end:math:display$

Parameters:

| Symbol | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| $begin:math:text$ \\alpha $end:math:text$ | curvature memory term |
| $begin:math:text$ \\beta $end:math:text$ | curvature flow term |
| $begin:math:text$ H\_0 $end:math:text$ | emergent motion rate |
| $begin:math:text$ \\tau $end:math:text$ | transition redshift scale |
| $begin:math:text$ \\text\{highz\} $end:math:text$ | high-z correction amplitude |
| $begin:math:text$ \\text\{quad\} $end:math:text$ | optional quadratic correction |

---

## 2.2 Luminosity Distance

$begin:math:display$
d\_L\(z\) \= d\_M\(z\)
\\left\[
1 \+ \\text\{highz\}\\cdot\\tanh\\\!\\left\(\\frac\{z\}\{\\tau\}\\right\)
\+ \\text\{quad\}\\\, z\^2
\\right\]
$end:math:display$

Distance modulus:

$begin:math:display$
\\mu\(z\) \= 5\\log\_\{10\}\(d\_L\) \+ 25
$end:math:display$

